        {
          "id": "/page/1/Text/1",
          "block_type": "Text",
          "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">In conclusion, a number of financial entities are necessary to create and maintain ETFs, indexed products that trade like stocks on major bourses. Furthermore, ETFs differ from mutual funds in that they trade throughout the day, can be shorted, and generally carry lower fees. Finally, the close to 2000 ETFs trading today cover a plethora of different investment categories, offering investors an inexpensive means to construct well-diversified portfolios.</p>",
